# Conventional Commit Template (Systems Projects)

# TYPE
# feat      = new user-visible functionality
# fix       = bug / race / crash / correctness issue
# refactor  = internal change, no behavior change
# perf      = latency / throughput / allocation improvement
# docs      = documentation only
# test      = tests added/changed
# build     = build / cmake / ci / compiler flags
# chore     = maintenance only
# style     = formatting only
# revert    = revert previous commit

# RULE:
# If behavior does NOT change → never use feat

# NEW FILE RULE
# header / interface only      → refactor
# real new capability          → feat
# optimization structure       → perf / refactor
# test scaffold                → test

# SCOPE
# Use subsystem, not filename
# Good: memtable, skiplist, wal, allocator, epoch
# Bad: code, misc, skiplist_node.hpp

# MULTIPLE FILES / FUNCTIONS
# Commit by ONE reason, not file count
# If one WHY → one commit
# If different WHYs → split commits

<type>(<scope>): <summary <= 60 chars>

- Why:
- Design decision:
- Impact: